## Intermediate Concepts## Q3: What is the difference between any and unknown?
Both can hold any value, but they enforce different levels of type safety: [7, 11] 

* any: Turns off type checking completely. You can call any method or property on it, which risks runtime crashes.
* unknown: A type-safe version of any. You cannot interact with an unknown variable until you safely narrow or assert its type. [11] 

let valueAny: any = "Hello";
valueAny.toUpperCase(); // Allowed
let valueUnknown: unknown = "Hello";// valueUnknown.toUpperCase(); // Compile Error!
if (typeof valueUnknown === "string") {
    valueUnknown.toUpperCase(); // Allowed after narrowing
}

## Q4: What is the difference between interface and type alias?
Both define custom data structures, but they have key structural trade-offs: [12] 

* Interfaces:
* Open for extension via declaration merging (declaring the same interface name multiple times merges their fields).
   * Strictly used to define object shapes. [13] 
* Type Aliases:
* Cannot be changed after creation (no declaration merging).
   * More flexible; can define primitives, unions, tuples, and intersections. [13, 14, 15] 

// Interface Declaration Merginginterface User { name: string; }interface User { age: number; } // Merged!
// Type Alias Uniontype ID = string | number;

## Q5: What is a Tuple?
A tuple is an array with a fixed number of elements where each element has a specific, known type. [11, 13] 

let employee: [number, string] = [1, "Alice"];// employee = ["Alice", 1]; // Compile Error! Wrong order.

