## Advanced Concepts## Q6: What are Generics and why would you use them?
Generics allow you to create reusable, type-flexible components that work across multiple types while maintaining type safety. Instead of locking a function into a single type or using any, you pass a type variable. [7, 16] 

function getFirstElement<T>(arr: T[]): T {
    return arr[0];
}
const numArr = getFirstElement<number>([1, 2, 3]); // Returns a numberconst strArr = getFirstElement<string>(["a", "b"]); // Returns a string

## Q7: What are Discriminated Unions?
A pattern used for type narrowing where a group of types share a common literal property (the "discriminant"). TypeScript reads this literal property to safely distinguish between the structures. [7] 

interface Success {
    status: "success"; // Discriminant
    data: string;
}
interface Failure {
    status: "failed"; // Discriminant
    error: string;
}
function handleResponse(res: Success | Failure) {
    if (res.status === "success") {
        console.log(res.data); // TypeScript knows res is 'Success'
    } else {
        console.log(res.error); // TypeScript knows res is 'Failure'
    }
}

## Q8: Explain Conditional Types. [17] 
Conditional types act like a ternary operator at the type level, choosing between two types based on a structural check (T extends U ? X : Y). [12, 18] 

type IsString<T> = T extends string ? true : false;
type A = IsString<string>; // Evaluates to: truetype B = IsString<number>; // Evaluates to: false

