## Scenario-Based Questions## Q9: How can you safely parse and validate runtime API JSON data into a type? [19] 
Using a type cast (as User) or a type annotation on JSON.parse is unsafe because it tells the compiler to blindly trust the shape, which can cause unexpected runtime crashes if the API schema changes. [11, 20] 
To handle this cleanly, you should use a User-Defined Type Guard function or an external validation library like Zod: [7, 13] 

type User = { name: string; age: number; };
// Type guard function safely checking properties at runtimefunction isUser(obj: any): obj is User {
    return obj && typeof obj.name === "string" && typeof obj.age === "number";
}
const data = `{"name":"Bob","age":30}`;const parsed = JSON.parse(data);
if (isUser(parsed)) {
    console.log(parsed.name.toLowerCase()); // Completely type-safe
}

## Q10: How do you enforce strict configuration matching without losing type inference? [21] 
Using a regular type declaration forces the compiler to broaden literal properties (e.g., matching "red" to just string). To strictly enforce an interface rule while preserving the exact literal values, you should use the satisfies operator. [7] 

interface ConnectionConfig {
    host: string;
    port: number;
}
// Validates against the interface but remembers that port is exactly 8080const config = {
    host: "localhost",
    port: 8080
} satisfies ConnectionConfig;
// Checking config.port here retains the precise literal type 8080 instead of 'number'

